    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today with **Austin Riley** (72.43) and **James Wood** (71.27) serving as the focal points of our offensive strategy. **Austin Riley** benefits from a rare alignment of a favorable park and a soft matchup against Irvin, whose high xERA suggests he will struggle to suppress power. Similarly, **James Wood** is our premier play, capitalizing on a leadoff spot against Elder; that order advantage, combined with solid park factors, makes him our highest-floor asset for R and SB potential. **Tyler Soderstrom** (68.84) also grades out as a strong start, as his platoon advantage against Hancock helps mitigate the park\u2019s suppressive nature.\n\nOur most difficult personnel decision centered on **Kyle Karros**, who sat on the bubble with a 44.69 score. While **Kyle Karros** benefits from a slow opposing pitcher delivery that would typically bolster his SB prospects, the combination of a difficult matchup against Wrobleski and the superior daily efficiency scores of **Alex Freeland** (61.84) and **Dalton Rushing** (57.87) kept him on the bench. We are wary of the risks today, particularly with the lineup status of **Dalton Rushing**, **Max Muncy**, **Seiya Suzuki**, and **Josh Naylor** still pending; should any of these bats be shuffled down the order, their efficiency scores will likely drop below our 50.00 threshold, potentially forcing a last-minute shift to our bench depth. We remain disciplined, however, keeping **Corbin Carroll**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Jose Caballero** unavailable due to the team's off-day, ensuring we don't burn precious roster spots while maintaining a focused look at our active contributors.",
